    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-04T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-04T21:00:00-05:00" n="756"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d756">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9411/73: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-05T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >April 5, 1941—9 [a.m.?]</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 5—6:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>127. The Foreign Minister<note n="40" xml:id="d756fn40">Wang Chung-hui.</note>
                    informed me yesterday that he had received a “reliable but unconfirmed” report
                    from Moscow to the effect that when Matsuoka was recently received by Stalin and
                    Molotov he approached the latter and suggested the continuation of negotiations
                    said to have been initiated during the incumbency of Litvinov as Soviet Foreign
                    Minister for the conclusion of a nonaggression pact between Japan and the Soviet
                    Union; and that Matsuoka was informed in reply that while it is the policy of
                    the Soviet Union to negotiate nonaggression pacts with its neighbors in the case
                    of Japan it would be necessary to bring about a restoration of the <hi
                        rend="italic">status quo ante</hi> of the Portsmouth Treaty<note n="41"
                        xml:id="d756fn41">Signed September 5, 1905, <ref target="frus1905#pg_824">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1905, p. 824</ref>.</note>
                    before the Soviet Union would consider the conclusion of such a pact with Japan.
                    The Foreign Minister, who seemed to think that the report had some basis in
                    fact, expressed the view that the Russian counterproposal was tantamount to a
                    “polite refusal” of Matsuoka’s proposal.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Peking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
